column4:
When it came to creative output, 2012 was a depressing year for me.  Much of my time and energy each week was lost to full-time work and daily life; the free time I had left over was fraught with fatigue or apathy, or spent dreading the coming work week.  I used a calendar to record days where I practiced my creative endeavors, as I had for years before.  Though it wasn't even the end of autumn, over six months had passed where only a handful of days were spent in pursuit of writing or photography.

I was painfully aware of my lack of creative output, reminded daily of my lack of progress, and discounting the progress I did make because of overly harsh self-criticism.  For someone who has been guided by creative expression since childhood, such a vast lack of output made me question the validity of my creative drive, and, at times, see myself as a failure for not pushing myself harder.

Given so much self-doubt and insecurity, when this subject caught my eye over a weeklong period in autumn, I photographed it more to operate my camera than to explore my imagination.  A few strands of spider web caught between windowpanes, with shrubs and sun in the background; I normally felt challenged by such a scene.  When this film returned from the lab, however, the difference between this image’s visualization and rendering was as massive as the decade-old photo that launched my passion for photography. 

I was entirely unprepared for the otherworldly, faux-astronomical event I saw, and found myself rediscovering a lesson that had long been my muse.  The rest of 2012 wasn't marked by any lasting increases in creative output, but the reminder that such magnificence is intertwined with our everyday lives, simply waiting to be recognized, was welcome, nonetheless.

column4:
Crumbling exterior walls of the Nabisco warehouse in Marseilles, IL.  I had photographed this same location years ago, but was unimpressed with the results.  This building and the other two that share its land have been vacant for as long as I can remember, and my frame of mind during that first photo outing was deeply influenced by such thoughts.  The buildings represented nothing more to me than urban decay in a stagnant area - my interest lay in the progression of decrepitude and nowhere else.  

Though I haven’t moved to many new homes, I’ve lived in far too many areas where massive plots of land are sold off for development without second thought, and I’ve grown tired of seeing splendid varieties of land, plant-life, and existing buildings reduced to sprawling asphalt lots or fluorescent-flooded concrete boxes - differentiated by nothing more than the unstoppable flood of vehicles, overabundance of branding, and accumulation of litter.  When I returned to this building in late March, 2013, I did so with a sense of fulfillment.  Fulfillment not because I had improved as a photographer and could render subjects that were once beyond my ability, but because of a growing appreciation of these buildings and their historic standing.

That March day was the first in months where I was both available to do my work, and granted safe passage by the weather and light...and stratocumulus clouds.  While waiting for the sun to break through on this particular shot, I contemplated a time when the door marked “2nd floor” didn't lead to a sharp drop, when the entrance wasn't lost in underbrush, and when being that far into the location wasn't something of a deviant activity.  I know little of the 
building now, apart from its general history, or know what occupied that land prior to the buildings, but I believe a crumbling facade and non-existent 2nd floor contribute more to the city’s character and identity than modern business architecture ever will.  However imperfectly the buildings have weathered time and however little utility they currently have, they represent an era of commerce and ingenuity, and affirm the city’s potential to thrive again.  In contrast, the best we’re given from modern business architecture is temporary ownership, or a large sign that reads “for sale or lease”.

Minolta XG 7
Minolta MD W.Rokkor-X 28mm f/2.8
Ilford Delta - ISO 100

column3: Old Guard at an Old Post
column4:
A random assortment of duct tape I found on a weathered barrel.  I had seen this barrel many times before, but on this particular day, it seemed as if I had met someone who’d seen the location far more times than I.  A soldier who returned not out of obligation, but perhaps out of duty, remorse, or to honor the past deeds of others (and who was endlessly patient with my ignorant wandering and lack of proper regard).

Minolta Maxxum 7
Minolta AF 70-210mm f/4
Kodak Ektar - ISO 100

column4:
Walking home from a failed shot, I found this rust and weathered paint on a large metal container for waste cardboard.  Despite being the service access to a thriving business, this particular lot was neglected to the point of abandonment - the sun and trapped litter were all that moved, nearby industrial air conditioning units held silent vigil in the heat.  I was intrigued by such desolation, but, discouraged from my previous shot, was also quick to see the lot and distant container as little more than plain geometry.

As I approached the container, imperfections on its surface were revealed, compounding at an incredible rate.  An insignificant patch of rust took shape, and I knew I had my picture - had it not been so long since I’d last seen an ocean, I would have looked upon that rust atop streaks of blue and white and heard nothing but approaching, receding waves.  I took my shot and continued on, but I imagined floating, waves choosing my path, for some time afterward.

Minolta Maxxum 7
Minolta AF 70-210mm f/4.5-5.6
Kodak Ektar - ISO 100

column4: I am sure the bar at Freiraum has been photographed multiple times, but it's just so much fun to look at. Whenever I'm at Freiraum, I love sitting at the table just to the left of the stairs and watching the hustle and bustle around this beautiful bar. Great place to also see who comes and goes at the restaurant/cafe.

column4: This is the most traditional and famous of ice cream parlors in Vienna. It's no where close to the center, but it's still iconic. It's in a bit of a seedier part of town (though Vienna is never really seedy), but the ice cream is very good. Not as good as Eis Greissler, but still very much worth a visit.

column4: This woman was so sweet with her granddaughter while in the park. Doting on her just like a grandmother should, they were the cutest to watch. I asked her if she would mind if I took their picture and she was absolutely in love with the idea. Got the little girl to pose a bit and everything - great experience for all involved.

column4: While I was walking through Stadtpark, about to head home and give up finding my last shot for this roll of film, I saw this girl walking around with an old SLR making photos. I struck her up and it turns out she's visiting from Russia, speaks a bit of English and loves film photography. I asked I could make her my final shot (it's so fitting somehow) and she made a shot of me, too. I gave her my card so that way she can email me when she develops hers. My card also has my Flickr page on it, so if you're seeing this, thanks for the awesome shot and memory!

column4:
The side of a painted concrete wall in my old apartment complex’s laundry room.  Of all the complaints I had with that complex, any involving their laundry services worked to my advantage here.  Having been alone for the duration of my time and not expecting otherwise, I retrieved my gear, set up my tripod, composed, and bracketed a couple shots. 

In the wasteland I saw through the viewfinder, snow bit deep through protective layers, and gathered into the shape of ancient burial mounds.  Distant features wandered, foraged, and vanished - hearing only wind, they were wholly unaware of the predatory surround.

Minolta XG7
Minolta MD 75-200mm f/4.5
Fomapan B&W - ISO 100

column4:
A remarkable boulder that I found while hiking in Giant City State Park of Illinois, USA.  Entranced as I was with its patterns and colors, I came to appreciate it far more as my hike progressed.  When I came to the Giant City Streets - immense sandstone bluffs formed over the course of 12,000 years - I found one bluff that bore a lengthy, well-preserved inscription.  I wasn't able to read it all, not wanting to block anyone when my gear alone nearly got me stuck in the narrow paths, but had time to read several names and dates (all in the mid to late 1800's), and hear another hiker admire the aged “penmanship”.  

I had to agree.  I can’t imagine the care that went into such a fine mix of swooping embellishments, rounded edges, and precise spacing, but hammer and chisel were wielded as a calligrapher’s pen.  As I walked on, searching for other subjects, I gave thought to this colorful boulder and the erratic, web-like hollowness that covered much of its surface - seeing a traveler’s name in each gossamer ridge, an eloquent description in each hollow cavity, and all of it inscribed where space allowed throughout 12,000 years.  

The chiseled, century-old inscription was certainly impressive, but I hold this boulder’s semblance of writing in a far higher regard.

Minolta Maxxum 7
Minolta AF 50mm f/2.8 Macro
Kodak Ektar - ISO 100

column4:
A retake of the same land I photographed years earlier.  Much of the land around these hills and trees has been developed for houses and roadways over the last 10-15 years.  In my youth, I remember gentle hills in place of cramped, cookie-cutter homes - grass, trees, and sky where there are now chain-link or solid fences blocking all sight.  The small town that houses this land cannot thrive or sustain itself without attracting new residents, and I support people making a home where their needs are best suited, but feel that both individual and community are better served by not filling every visible inch of land with lifeless asphalt and bargain-basement housing.

With the constant cycle of construction we live in - buildings rising, being occupied, changing hands, lying empty, etc. - land that appears as it was long before our arrival, and as it will long after we’re gone is a haven.  It is free, while the chaotic sprawl of fences and windowless siding are restrained; welcoming, while glowing TVs illuminate drawn curtains as a quarantine.

To be fair, I also remember the paved, widened, and erosion-resistant road that runs through the same area having once been gravel and studded with potholes.  Updating that road was an obvious benefit to the town as a whole, if one that - in my mind - came at a great cost.

Minolta Maxxum 7
Minolta AF 28mm f/2.8
Kodak Ektar - ISO 100
